  GRAPH narr:Tx_20260519T180000Z {

    # Document-level narrative: the convergence pattern
    narr:Narrative_ForgettingBottleneckIsRole a narr:Narrative ;
      dct:source narr:Sample_CustomerEngManagerVision_20260519 ;
      skos:broader narr:FrictionFailure ;
      skos:prefLabel "The Forgetting Bottleneck Is a Role, Not a Person" ;
      skos:note "Two senior the enterprise customer people — the customer's chief architect (chief architect) and an engineering manager at the customer (development manager, ARB facilitator) — independently described themselves the same way: as candidates for aswritten precisely because they forget as much as they remember. The bottleneck is not scarce expertise; it is scarce memory at the decision junction. Anyone who sits where many decisions and many threads cross will say what an engineering manager at the customer and the customer's chief architect said, because the role asks a human to hold more than a human holds. The convergence was surfaced by the citation tool reaching for the customer's chief architect when processing a draft that quoted an engineering manager at the customer — because the perspective held the customer's chief architect's version of the sentiment and not an engineering manager at the customer's." ;
      narr:theme "The forgetting bottleneck is structural to the decision-junction role, not personal to any individual — two independent self-diagnoses from different roles confirm the pattern" .

    # Claim: an engineering manager at the customer's self-identification
    narr:Claim_CustomerEngManagerSelfIDBottleneck a narr:Claim ;
      dct:source narr:Sample_CustomerEngManagerVision_20260519 ;
      skos:note "an engineering manager at the customer — development manager at the enterprise customer, eight direct reports across two teams, ARB facilitator — said unprompted: 'I'm a key candidate for this because I forget as much as I remember.' The detail that matters is the role: this is the facilitator talking, not a junior developer losing the thread, but the person whose job is to hold the thread. He extended it: 'It's impossible for me to remember, oh, we do or don't support this odd case. If a customer comes with a specific use case, it's difficult for me to remember.'" ;
      narr:aboutNode narr:Narrative_ForgettingBottleneckIsRole ;
      narr:hasConvictionLevel narr:Conviction_Foundation ;
      .

    # Claim: buyer is plural
    narr:Claim_ConvergenceBuyerIsPlural a narr:Claim ;
      dct:source narr:Sample_CustomerEngManagerVision_20260519 ;
      skos:note "The ARB use case has been framed around the expert as bottleneck — the senior person the rest of the team waits on. an engineering manager at the customer and the customer's chief architect together sharpen it: the bottleneck is not scarce expertise but scarce memory at the decision junction. Consequence: the buyer is plural. Not a single irreplaceable expert, but every senior person at a decision junction — and an engineering organization has several. The 'expert as bottleneck' story is really a 'decision junction' story, and decision junctions repeat." ;
      narr:aboutNode narr:Narrative_ForgettingBottleneckIsRole ;
      narr:hasConvictionLevel narr:Conviction_Boulder ;
      narr:supports narr:Narrative_EnterpriseShapePrimaryFocus .

    # Claim: self-identification as qualifying signal
    narr:Claim_SelfIDAsQualifyingSignal a narr:Claim ;
      dct:source narr:Sample_CustomerEngManagerVision_20260519 ;
      skos:note "When a customer contact says some version of 'I forget as much as I remember,' they have already diagnosed their own need. an engineering manager at the customer said it unprompted; so did the customer's chief architect. This is the cleanest buying signal the ARB use case produces — worth listening for by name in discovery calls. The self-identification is the qualifying signal." ;
      narr:aboutNode narr:Narrative_ForgettingBottleneckIsRole ;
      narr:hasConvictionLevel narr:Conviction_Boulder ;
      narr:supports narr:Narrative_EnterpriseShapePrimaryFocus .

    # Claim: options vs decisions verbatim — sharpest customer-language version
    narr:Claim_OptionsVsDecisionsVerbatim a narr:Claim ;
      dct:source narr:Sample_CustomerEngManagerVision_20260519 ;
      skos:note "an engineering manager at the customer's verbatim account of the options-versus-decisions distinction that drives the day-to-day re-litigation problem: 'We gave you pros and cons and you were to go away and figure out which one suits and come back with a proposal. We didn't give you a full solution, we just gave you options.' Re-litigation happens when a recipient collapses that open set into a single remembered decision. The distinction — offered versus agreed, options versus solution — is what the perspective must preserve and a static record cannot. This is the sharpest customer-language version aswritten has of this problem." ;
      narr:aboutNode narr:Narrative_DayToDayRelitigation ;
      narr:hasConvictionLevel narr:Conviction_Foundation ;
      narr:supports narr:Claim_InterpretationPreservation .

